{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567577"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:04:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:04:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19134"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19134"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.24,0.07,0.2,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11868"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82351"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11868"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67549"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4555"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28156"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82351"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following a fall onto concrete, sustaining a 5 cm laceration to her shin. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The wound is clean but there is a considerable amount of exudate. There is no evidence of infection, bone injury, or neurovascular compromise.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate dressing for this wound?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydrocolloid dressing","Paraffin gauze dressing","Film dressing","Foam adhesive dressing","Calcium alginate dressing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an open wound that has a considerable amount of exudate. It will require appropriate dressing selection to optimise healing. The key considerations in dressing selection include the amount of exudate, wound depth, and presence of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium alginate dressings\u003C/strong\u003E are ideal for moderate to heavily exudating wounds. They are derived from seaweed and form a gel when in contact with wound exudate, maintaining a moist environment while absorbing excess fluid. This gel also aids in autolytic debridement and can conform to wound contours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocolloid dressings\u003C/strong\u003E are more suitable for wounds with light to moderate exudate. They form a gel over time but have limited absorption capacity and may lead to maceration of surrounding tissue if used on heavily exudating wounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFilm dressings\u003C/strong\u003E are transparent, adhesive sheets that are waterproof but non-absorbent. They are inappropriate for exudating wounds and are better suited for superficial wounds or as secondary dressings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParaffin gauze dressings\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily used for superficial wounds or grafts where adherence to the wound bed needs to be minimised. They provide minimal absorption and would be insufficient for managing heavy exudate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFoam adhesive dressings\u003C/strong\u003E can absorb moderate amounts of exudate but may not be as effective as alginates in managing heavy exudate. They are better suited for wounds with moderate exudate or where cushioning is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter selecting an appropriate primary dressing, a secondary dressing may be required to secure the alginate in place and provide additional protection. The dressing should be reviewed regularly and changed when saturated to maintain an optimal healing environment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Heavily exudating wounds require highly absorbent dressings to maintain an optimal healing environment.","Alginate dressings are ideal for moderate to heavily exudating wounds as they form a gel when in contact with wound fluid.","The choice of wound dressing should consider the amount of exudate, wound depth, and presence of infection."],"references":["Sinha et al. The art and science of selecting appropriate dressings for acute open wounds in general practice. 2022. Australian Journal of General Practice. https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/november/selecting-appropriate-dressings"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67549"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19134"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67549"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T16:39:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T16:40:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11868"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82351"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","link